\begin_layout Standard
The basis of this study is the following setting: we have a population of
 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 individuals.
 Each individual has a personal skill 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{real}$
\end_inset

 that is composed of two independent skill-features 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
s_{real}=\frac{1}{2}\left(x_{1}+x_{2}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We call it 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

real
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 because we will differentiate it from observed and from predicted/assumed
 skill and from the skill that the labor market (
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

recruiters
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

) assigns to the inviduals later on.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In addition, each individual has a binary protected attribute 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{pr}$
\end_inset

 that can have values of 0 and 1.
 In reality this could for example be gender, but here it is used in an
 abstract way.
 Central here is that the definition if 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{real}$
\end_inset

 does not contain 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{pr}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We draw 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 from truncated normal distributions.
 Normal distributions because personal features such as 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

talent
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 are usually assumed to be normally distributed (e.g.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "biondoTalentVsLuck2018"
literal "false"

\end_inset

).
 A truncated normal distribution is used instead of an untrancated one to
 ensure that no one has 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and/or 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

