\begin_layout Subsection
Complex Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Our second model is more complex and slightly more realistic than the simple
 dynamical model.
 While it was designed with the dynamics of the real-world AMS-system in
 mind, it is still highly abstract and should not be confused with a complete
 model of labour market dynamics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Population model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

natural
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 distribution of skill in the population we use the same model as for the
 simple model.
 The difference is that in the simple model, the population is fixed, with
 an initial distribution of skill.
 For the complex model, we assume that there is an (unlimited) 
\emph on
background-population 
\emph default
pool with the distribution of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1},x_{2},x_{pr}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{real}$
\end_inset

 described by eqs (1-4).
 This background population and the distribution of the features of the
 individuals does not change throughout a model run, but acts as a pool
 for refilling the pool of job-seekers.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Labor market model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The labor market is modeled via a probabilistic function that for each individua
l defines the probability of finding a job at the current timestep, where
 this probability depends on 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{real}$
\end_inset

 of that individual.
 We model the dependence on 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{real}$
\end_inset

 as a logistic function:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
P\left(job|s_{real}\right)=\frac{1}{1+e^{-(\alpha_{l}s_{real}+\beta_{l})}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{l}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{l}$
\end_inset

 are parameters that need to be set a priori.
 At each timestep, 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(job|s_{real}\right)$
\end_inset

 is computed for each individual on the pool of job-seekers.
 Each individual is removed from the pool of job seekers with probability
 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The choice for a logistic labor market function was made because it satisfies
 the following intuition about the labor-market: If an individual has very
 low skill, than the probability of finding a job is very low (close to
 zero), and if the skill slightly increases, then the chance is still very
 low.
 There is a soft threshold which one needs to reach in order to have a reasonabl
e chance.
 Above this soft threshold, increases in 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{real}$
\end_inset

 have a strong impact, and the higher skilled one is, the higher the chances
 of finding a job.
 Eventually, however, this reaches a plateau, as the probability of finding
 a job is already close to 1, and additional skill does basically not change
 anything anymore.
 The parameters 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{l}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{l}$
\end_inset

 define this 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

middle
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 region in which changes of 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{real}$
\end_inset

 have a strong impact on the probability.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta_{l}$
\end_inset

 defines the position of this middle region, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha_{l}$
\end_inset

 how broad/steep it is.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that we made 
\begin_inset Formula $P\left(job|s_{real}\right)$
\end_inset

 independent of the time an individual is already unemployed.
 The intuition behind is that in our idealized setting, the skill of an
 individual is solely defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{real}$
\end_inset

, which the labor market knows.
 Therefore, in this setting, the fact that someone has been unemployed for
 a long time does not yield additional information about their skill.
 In reality this might not necessarily be the case, as long-term unemployment
 as additional information could be a reason for an employer to not hire
 someone.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Public Employment Service
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similar to the simple model, the PES in the complex model uses a logistic
 regression model that classifies individuals as either low or high prospect,
 with 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and optionally 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{pr}$
\end_inset

 as predictors.
 The classes are, however, not defined by setting a threshold on 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{real}$
\end_inset

, but by setting a threshold on the time 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{u}$
\end_inset

 that it took individuals in the historical record to find a job.
 This history is continuously build up throughout a modelrun with all individual
s that found a job.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Intervention Model
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The treatment of individuals differs between the high and the low prospect
 group in two ways: in the amount of help (increase of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

) they receive, and how long this help takes.
 The highprospect group receives the help immediately, and is available
 on the labor-market in the next timestep.
 The low-prospect group, on the other hand, receives help that takes time
 and removes them from the labor-market for a period of time 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta T_{u}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The change of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{2}$
\end_inset

 under different scenarios is modeled in the same way as for the simple
 model (see section 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "subsec:Intervention-Model"
plural "false"
caps "false"
noprefix "false"

\end_inset

).
 Since individuals classified as low-prospect are removed from the active
 group for 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta T_{u}$
\end_inset

 timesteps , there skill is updated 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta T_{u}+1$
\end_inset

 times (by applying eqs 9-10) to account for that.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An important difference, however, is that in the simple model, it is easy
 to know the true prospect of an individual (as it is solely defined by
 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{real}$
\end_inset

).
 In the complex model, this is less straightforward.
 Here, the prospect is the 
\emph on
expected
\emph default
 time 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{u}$
\end_inset

 that the individual will be unemployed.
 The real time that this individual will need cannot be known, as it 1)
 evolves from the model and 2) is linked to 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{real}$
\end_inset

, but only in a 
\emph on
probabilistic
\emph default
 way.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For the complex model, we therefore defined the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

real prospect
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 of an individual as 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{u}$
\end_inset

 estimated from the historical data, using 
\begin_inset Formula $s_{real}$
\end_inset

 as predictor (in contrast to the predicted prospect, which uses 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{1}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{prot}$
\end_inset

 as predictor).
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This real prospect (grouped into below or above the fixed threshold) is
 then used in the scenarios (only in those scenarios in which it makes a
 difference if an individual is classified incorrectly)
\end_layout

